content:
A Data Mapper is a mapping tool that enables you to read, transform, and write Salesforce data. There are four types of Data Mapper: Turbo Extract, Extract, Transform, and Load.

Turbo Extract reads data from a single Salesforce object type, with support for fields from related objects. Then select the fields to include. Formulas and complex field mappings arenâ€™t supported.

Extract reads data from Salesforce objects and output JSON or XML with complex field mappings. Formulas are supported.

Transform performs intermediate data transformations without reading from or writing to Salesforce. Formulas are supported.

Load updates Salesforce data from JSON or XML input. Formulas are supported.

Data Mappers typically supply data to OmniScripts, Integration Procedures, and Cards, and write updates from OmniScripts, Integration Procedures, and Cards to Salesforce.

A Data Mapper can access external objects and custom metadata as well as sObjects. No special syntax or additional configuration is required.

There are four types of Data Mapper: Turbo Extract, Extract, Transform, and Load.

Data Mapper Turbo Extract retrieves data from a single Salesforce object type, with support for fields from related objects.

Data Mapper Extract reads Salesforce data and return results in JSON, XML, or custom formats. Formulas, attributes, default values, and translations are supported.

Data Mapper Transform lets you perform intermediate data transformations without reading from or writing to Salesforce. Formulas are supported.

Data Mapper Load accepts data in JSON, XML, or custom input formats and write the data to Salesforce objects. Formulas and attributes are supported.

You can define formulas to add data to the output of a Data Mapper. Several types of Data Mapper (Extract, Transform, and Load) support formulas.

Many data types can be assigned to data in the Output JSON, including boolean, currency, string, various number and list types, and date formats.

Data Mappers have additional caching, security, batch, and debug settings. You can also export and deploy Data Mappers.

Using a cache to store frequently accessed, infrequently updated Data Mapper data saves round trips to the database and improves performance.

You can control access to Data Mappers using settings that reference Sharing Settings and Sharing Sets or Profiles and Permission Sets.
title: Omnistudio Data Mappers
